How to add ISU for an Integration?

Step 1: Select the integration link's related action by clicking it. Navigate to "Workday Account" and select "Edit".

Step 2: Once you have selected "Edit", a micropage will appear where you can choose your preferred ISU. After making your selection, click "OK" to proceed.

How to make the schedule is owned by ISU?

Step 1: Select the integration link's related action, and select the "Reports" and then "Scheduled Future Processes".

Step 2: Before proceeding, please confirm that the desired integration has been selected. Once verified, click the "OK" button to proceed.

Step 3: After clicking the "OK" button, you will be directed to schedule a future process. In the specific row, select the related action for values in the "Schedule Process" column, Go to "Schedule Future Process" and select "Transfer Ownership".

Step 4: After selecting "Transfer Ownership," you will be directed to another page where you can choose the "ISU" for that particular scheduled process. Then click the "OK" button to proceed.

How to make an integration template deprecated?

Step 1: Select the integration link's related action. Next, navigate to "Deployments" and select "Mark Instance as Do Not Use."

How to create schedule for an integration?

Step 1: Select the integration link's related action and choose "Integration" from the menu that appears. Next, click on "Launch/Schedule" to proceed.

Step 2: After selecting "Launch/Schedule," you will be directed to a micropage where you can enter the "Run Frequency." Be sure to fill out all required fields before clicking "OK." Once you have added all the necessary details, click "OK" to proceed as shown in the image below.

How to know the integration status?

  • This page displays a summary of each integration event's details, including the event's status, such as whether it was successfully completed or not.
  • The column labeled as "1" in the image displays the names of integration events, which include the integration name, date and status.
  • The column labeled as "2" in the image indicates the person who ran the particular integration, providing information on who initiated the integration.
  • The column labeled as "3" in the image displays the exact date and time when the integration was run, providing a timestamp for when the integration was initiated.
  • The column labeled as "4" in the image displays the status of the integration event, indicating whether the integration was completed successfully, completed with errors, or completed with warnings.
  • The table below provides a brief description of the integration event status, helping to clarify what each status means and providing additional context for the information displayed in the column labeled as "4" in the image.

    • Status Description
    Aborted An integration administrator stopped the integration event.
    Completed The background process completed with no warning or error messages.
    Completed with errors The background process completed with 1 or more error messages, but no critical messages. This status indicates an issue that you can resolve. It includes Studio integrations that don't complete successfully within the Studio integration runtime boundaries.
    Completed with warnings The background process completed with 1 or more warning messages, but no critical or error messages.
    Failed The background process had a nonrecoverable critical error that caused it to abort. For Workday-delivered integrations, this status can indicate a product defect or service issue.
    Not Run due to Exceptions on Future Process Workday couldn't run the background process because the integration has critical exceptions. Example: the EIB or schedule owner has insufficient security.
    Processing The background process is running.
